34. The story begins in the middle, as in the Odyssey (in medias res . . . auditorem rapit, Hor., Ars Poetica, 148). The Trojans are sailing round Sicily to avoid the dangerous Strait of Messina (iii. 562), and have just left Drepanum (iii. 707; see map). The earlier adventures device to rouse interest (as in many modern novels). Cf. also Paradise Lost, which, as Milton himself says, “hastes into the midst of thingS, presenting Satan with his angels now fallen into hell” (see i. 50), the story of their fall not being fully told till book v, vv. -563 ff.
